Vector data

Importing and exporting vector data

Vector data are composed of discrete geometric locations (lon, lat) known as vertices that define the shape of the spatial object. Vertices determines the type of vector that you are working with: points, lines and polygons.

Vector point data can be stored in regular delimited text files

# open records of occurrence
distributionRecords <- read.table('Data/dataBases/MergedCoordinates.csv',sep=';',header=TRUE)
head(distributionRecords)
Lon Lat
11.080359 42.41853
10.836515 42.31011
15.469765 42.06097
3.297701 42.04394
S2 // R as a Geographic Information System

# plot distribution records as red circles
plot(distributionRecords, main='Distribution of Paramuricea clavata')

S2 // R as a Geographic Information System

Vector line data can be stored in a shapefile format. The package raster deals with shapefiles.

# load raster package
library(raster)
# load a line vector shapefile
coastline <- shapefile('Data/vectorShapefiles/coastlines/ne_10m_coastline.shp')
# plot spatial line vector
plot(coastline, main = 'Global coastline', col='gray', axes=TRUE)

S2 // R as a Geographic Information System

Vector polygon data can be stored in a shapefile format.

# load a line vector shapefile
landMass <- shapefile('Data/vectorShapefiles/globalLandmass/world.shp')
# plot spatial polygon vector with a title
plot(landMass, main = 'Global landmass', col='gray', axes=TRUE)

S2 // R as a Geographic Information System

To overlay points from with vector layers in a plot use points.

plot(landMass, main='Distribution of a coral', col='Gray', border='Gray', axes=TRUE)
points(distributionRecords, pch=20)

S2 // R as a Geographic Information System

To overlay multiple vector layers in a plot use the add=TRUE argument.

seagrass <- shapefile("Data/vectorShapefiles/seagrass/cymodoceaNodosa.shp")
plot(landMass, main='Distribution of a seagrass', col='Gray', border='Gray', axes=TRUE)
plot(seagrass, pch=20, add=TRUE)

Vector data operations

Operations that change the geometry of spatial vector objects.

Crop vector data

# read landmass from an R package
globalLandmass <- shapefile('Data/vectorShapefiles/globalLandmass/world.shp')

# generate an extent object (region of interest, xmin,xmax,ymin,ymax)
westAfricaExtent <- extent(-30, 22, -37.5, 36)
S2 // R as a Geographic Information System

plot(globalLandmass, main = 'Global landmass', col='gray', border='gray', axes = TRUE)
plot(westAfricaExtent, border='black',add=TRUE)

S2 // R as a Geographic Information System

westAfricaLandmass <- crop(globalLandmass,westAfricaExtent)
plot(westAfricaLandmass, main = 'West Africa landmass', col='gray', border='gray',axes = TRUE)

Raster data

Raster data

Raster data comes as an image representing a portion of the earth, using a regular grid. The raster package deals with multi-layer data using a RasterStack.

# Open a raster layer with the global sst
SST <- raster('Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/OceanTemperature Surface Pred Mean.tif')
# Plot a raster layer
plot(SST , main='Global sea surface temperature')

S2 // R as a Geographic Information System

# Open all layers inside a folder
environmentalData <- stackDirectory('Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/')
# Plot raster layers
plot(environmentalData)

Raster data operations

Crop raster data

# load the raster layer
presentSST <- raster('Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/OceanTemperature Surface Pred Mean.tif')

# define the extent to crop [xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax]
westAfricaExtent <- extent(-30, 22, -37.5, 36)
S2 // R as a Geographic Information System

# plot temperature 
plot(presentSST, main='Global sea surface temperatures')
# plot region of interest
plot(westAfricaExtent, add=TRUE)

S2 // R as a Geographic Information System

# crop with polygon (region)
westAfricaPresentSST <- crop(SST,westAfricaExtent)
plot(westAfricaPresentSST, main='West Africa sea surface temperature')

S2 // R as a Geographic Information System

Raster data operations

Mask raster data

# load the raster layer
SST <- raster('Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/OceanTemperature Surface Pred Mean.tif')
# load the raster mask
maskCoastal <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/CoastLine.tif")
# plot the raster mask
plot(maskCoastal, col="black")

S2 // R as a Geographic Information System

# mask with raster layer (region)
CoastalSST <- mask(SST,maskCoastal)
# plot the masked layer
plot(CoastalSST, main='Coastal sea surface temperature')
